equation_narrative.headline: Hydrophobic representation shifts to charged arginine via late-layer MLP decision channels
equation_narrative.story: Through layer 23, the model assembles a representation dominated by hydrophobic character—valine, leucine, and alanine lead the logit lens, peaking at 23% (V at L14). This reflects the model reading local hydrophobic contacts (L, I, F at adjacent positions) and structural environment. The representation remains ambiguous about charge until L24, when arginine-specific MLP neurons activate decisively. Between L24-31, R surges from 17% to 89% as prediction channels fire (N24:4998 with 0.93 projection, N31:2273 with 1.50 projection), overriding the hydrophobic signal. The model correctly identifies this as a charged position despite early hydrophobic-leaning context.

perception_phase.summary: Layers 1-23 build a representation strongly biased toward hydrophobic residues. The logit lens shows valine leading from L13-23 (peaking at 23.2% at L14), with leucine, alanine, and isoleucine also prominent. This reflects the model reading 6 structural contacts and local sequence context rich in hydrophobic residues (L, I, F at positions 43-46). Attention heads at L11 (H2, +1.32 projection) and early MLP layers write hydrophobic-consistent features. The representation character is hydrophobic-core-like through L20, with frequent lead changes between small hydrophobics (A, V, I, L). Only 3 co-evolving positions provide signal, suggesting limited evolutionary constraint. The representation begins shifting toward charged character at L20-23 as lysine briefly leads (18.0% at L20), but valine reclaims dominance until the perception-decision boundary.
perception_phase.context_character: The assembled context through L23 is predominantly hydrophobic with local sequence enriched in leucine and isoleucine. The representation is consistent with a buried or partially buried position, though the brief emergence of lysine at L20 hints at surface-accessible character that will dominate the decision phase.
key_information_sources: Structural contacts: 6 residues within contact distance, chemistry not fully specified but local sequence shows L43, I44, F45 adjacent
Co-evolutionary signal: 3 coupled positions provide modest constraint, insufficient to override local hydrophobic bias early
L9 attention features: F9:5728 (53.95 proj), F9:1281 (49.31 proj) encode early representation character
L18 features: F18:5063 (39.36 proj) maintains hydrophobic-consistent representation through mid-layers

decision_phase.summary: The decision crystallizes at L24 when arginine overtakes valine (17.0% vs 15.9%) and never relinquishes the lead. MLP neurons become the dominant drivers: N24:4998 contributes +0.93 projection for R, followed by massive support from N31:2273 (+1.50 projection) and N31:4830 (+0.99 projection). By L29, R reaches 64.11% and climbs to 94.72% at L33. The decision phase is characterized by strong arginine-specific prediction channels activating while hydrophobic candidates (L, V, M) collapse from their early prominence.
decision_phase.transition: At L23-24, the representation shifts from encoding hydrophobic context to committing to a charged residue. L23 shows V still leading at 15.94% with R at only 6.07%, but L24 MLP (total +3.70 answer projection) drives R to 17.0%. This marks the first sustained arginine lead and the activation of amino-acid-specific prediction features rather than context-encoding features.

candidates.narrative: Arginine emerges as the winner through decisive MLP neuron activation in L24-33. Despite representing only 6-9% through L23, R surges when prediction channels activate: N24:4998 (+0.93 proj), N29:1659 (+0.64 proj), N31:2273 (+1.50 proj), and N31:4830 (+0.99 proj) all vote strongly for arginine. Structural attention at L28 (H1, +1.88 projection) and L31 (H17, +1.67 projection) reinforce the decision. R reaches 64.11% by L29 and 94.72% at final output, dominating all other candidates.
candidates.key_layers: Takes lead at L24, dominant by L29, peaks at L33
key_evidence: N24:4998 (MLP, +0.93 proj) — R/K-specific neuron, first major arginine vote
N31:2273 (MLP, +1.50 proj) — strongest single neuron, R-dominant with 1.50 projection
L28 H1 structural writer (+1.88 proj, 37.6% structural attention)
N29:1659 (MLP, +0.64 proj) — P/N/R-voting neuron supporting charged residues

candidates.narrative: Valine dominates the logit lens from L13-23, peaking at 23.24% at L14, reflecting the hydrophobic character of the representation during perception. The model is not predicting valine—rather, the accumulated features (local hydrophobic contacts, buried-position encoding) happen to project most strongly onto valine in logit space. V collapses rapidly in the decision phase, dropping from 15.94% at L23 to 0.75% at L29 as arginine-specific prediction channels override the hydrophobic representation.
candidates.key_layers: Leads L13-23, peaks at L14, eliminated by L29
key_evidence: Logit lens shows 23.24% at L14 during peak hydrophobic representation phase
MLP erasers at L14-15 (N14:3762 -0.54 proj, N15:3651 -0.41 proj) begin suppressing hydrophobics
Drops to 0.75% at L29 as decision-phase MLP neurons vote for charged residues

candidates.narrative: Leucine is the second-place finisher at 2.59%, representing residual hydrophobic signal that persists through the decision phase. L shows early strength (13.69% at L0, 16.04% peak at L10) during the hydrophobic representation phase. Unlike valine, leucine maintains modest support into late layers through neurons like N30:2016 (+0.73 proj voting L>R) and N32:1163 (+0.68 proj voting M>L>R), but cannot compete with the overwhelming arginine-specific channels.
candidates.key_layers: Early presence L0-L17, persists weakly through L33
key_evidence: N30:2016 (MLP, +0.73 proj for R but 0.98 for L) — mixed hydrophobic/charged voting
N32:1163 (MLP, +0.68 proj for R, 0.80 for L) — maintains leucine as viable alternative
Final 2.59% represents unresolved hydrophobic component of context

candidates.narrative: Methionine maintains steady low-level support (1-4%) throughout all layers, peaking at 3.75% at L11. As a long hydrophobic residue with some polar character, M represents a compromise candidate that never gains decisive support. Several late-layer neurons vote for M alongside R (N28:3528 votes M>R with 0.59 vs 0.49 projection), but these mixed signals are insufficient against the strong arginine-specific channels.
candidates.key_layers: Steady 1-4% across all layers, peaks at L11
key_evidence: N28:3528 (MLP, +0.49 proj for R, 0.59 for M) — mixed voting pattern
Final 2.25% shows persistent but weak hydrophobic alternative signal

turning_points.description: The representation shifts from small hydrophobics (alanine) to branched hydrophobics (valine). Alanine leads at 29.9% at L13, then valine takes over at L14 (23.2%). MLP neurons at L14-15 drive this transition with strong negative projections (N14:3762 -0.54, N15:3651 -0.41) that begin suppressing the small-hydrophobic character. This reflects the model refining its understanding of the position's size and burial constraints, moving from generic hydrophobic to bulkier hydrophobic residues.

The perception-to-decision transition occurs here. At L23, valine still leads (15.94%) with R at only 6.07%. L24 MLP delivers +3.70 total answer projection, driven by N24:4998 (+0.93 for R). Arginine takes the lead at 17.0% and never relinquishes it. This marks the activation of amino-acid-specific prediction channels (high-enrichment features for R/K) rather than context-encoding features. The representation shifts from 'this position has hydrophobic neighbors' to 'this position is arginine.'

Arginine surges from 64.11% to 89.4% as the strongest MLP neurons fire. N29:1659 (+0.64 proj), N31:2273 (+1.50 proj), and N31:4830 (+0.99 proj) deliver decisive votes for arginine. Structural attention heads at L31 (H17 +1.67 proj, H7 -2.20 eraser) simultaneously write arginine signal and erase competing hydrophobic candidates. This is the final commitment phase where the model consolidates its decision and suppresses all alternatives.

deep_dives.label: Early hydrophobic features L1-L18
deep_dives.caption: These features encode the hydrophobic character that dominates the representation through L23. F9:5728 (53.95 proj) and F18:5063 (39.36 proj) show how the model builds a hydrophobic-consistent representation from local sequence and structural contacts, which the logit lens projects onto V/L/A—not as predictions, but as the chemical character of the assembled context.

deep_dives.label: Structural attention L28-L31
deep_dives.caption: L28 H1 (+1.88 proj, 37.6% structural attention) and L31 H17 (+1.67 proj, 24.1% structural attention) read distant structural contacts to write arginine signal. These heads are the primary mechanism for incorporating 3D spatial information into the decision, overriding the local hydrophobic bias.

deep_dives.label: MLP decision onset L24-L25
deep_dives.caption: L24 marks the first major arginine vote: N24:4998 contributes +0.93 projection with strong R/K specificity (0.93 for R, 0.86 for K). Total L24 MLP projection is +3.70 for the answer. This is where prediction channels activate and the model commits to a charged residue, overriding 23 layers of hydrophobic representation.

deep_dives.label: MLP consolidation L29-L31
deep_dives.caption: The strongest arginine-specific neurons fire here. N31:2273 delivers +1.50 projection (the single largest contribution), N31:4830 adds +0.99, and N29:1659 contributes +0.64. These neurons have high R-specificity and drive the final surge from 64% to 89%. Examine their voting patterns to see how the model distinguishes R from K and other charged residues.

deep_dives.label: Late SAE features L30-L33
deep_dives.caption: L33 features show extreme projections (F33:7063 at 156.72, F33:2789 at 143.70), indicating high-confidence arginine-specific prediction channels. These are the final readout features that translate the MLP neuron votes into logit space. Compare to L30 features to see how confidence builds in the final layers.

deep_dives.label: Velocity events L14-L15
deep_dives.caption: L14-15 show large negative velocity (away from answer) as the model suppresses small hydrophobics in favor of bulkier ones. L14 total delta is -2.16 (attention-driven), L15 is -3.36 (MLP-driven). This is part of the perception phase refinement, not a decision-level error—the model is narrowing the representation from 'generic hydrophobic' to 'bulky hydrophobic' before ultimately pivoting to charged.

equation_narrative.resolution: The model correctly predicts arginine by assembling a hydrophobic-biased representation through L23, then decisively overriding it with charged-residue prediction channels in L24-33. The strongest evidence comes from MLP neurons at L24 (N24:4998, +0.93) and L31 (N31:2273, +1.50; N31:4830, +0.99) that vote specifically for arginine, combined with structural attention heads (L28 H1, L31 H17) that read distant contacts. The early hydrophobic signal (V leading at 23% through L14-23) reflects the local sequence context, not a misunderstanding—the model correctly interprets this as context to be integrated, not as the answer itself. The 94.72% final confidence reflects strong convergence of structural, evolutionary, and sequence-based evidence for a positively charged residue at this position.
